			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1236817">
									

<p>It's interesting, but the unanswered questions I have still prevent me from liking it too much- like, how do researchers know that these aren't schizophrenic hallucinations, or that there aren't multiple types of them that all look different (why go to the assumption that they're one species?) Have non-schizophrenic people seen them eat anything, or turn them into more 870's? How often does this happen, for it not to be noticed in big cities? (Do they wait till the prey are in secluded areas, like their own houses, or not eat plants and such in public?) Do we have any guesses as to why only schizophrenics can see them?</p>
<p>&#8230;You probably shouldn't answer all of these directly in the article, but what I mean is, this doesn't sound credible enough for me to be able to run with it. Think about how scientists would approach something like this. And I <em>like</em> the concept a bunch, but I feel like you should expand on it.</p>

